---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;
---

<Layout
  title={`Prompt-to-Ontology — ${config.site.title}`}
  description="A method for converting messy business language, requirements, and process concepts into structured entities, relationships, constraints, and actions for enterprise AI."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main pageTitle="Prompt-to-Ontology" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Prompt-to-Ontology is a method for converting messy business language,
      requirements, and process concepts into structured entities,
      relationships, constraints, and actions.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Why Ontology Matters</h2>
    <p>
      Most enterprise AI projects fail at the data modeling layer. Not because
      the model is bad, but because the system doesn't understand the business.
      An ontology forces you to define what exists, how things are connected,
      and what operations are possible. Without this, agents reason about a
      fictional version of your business.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">From Requirement to Ontology</h2>
    <ol class="mt-2 list-inside list-decimal space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Extract entities</strong> — What are the nouns? Orders, customers,
        products, machines, incidents. Name them explicitly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Identify relationships</strong> — How do entities connect? Customers
        place orders. Orders contain products. Machines produce batches.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Define attributes</strong> — What properties does each entity have?
        Status, timestamp, quantity, priority, owner.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add constraints</strong> — What rules govern the domain? An order
        can't ship before payment. A machine can't run two batches simultaneously.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Map possible actions</strong> — What operations can be performed on
        each entity? Create, update, approve, cancel, escalate.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Connect to agent workflows</strong> — How does the ontology power
        agent reasoning? Entities become tool inputs, actions become tool outputs,
        constraints become guardrails.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Example Pattern</h2>
    <p>
      A messy requirement like "the system should help manage inventory"
      becomes:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Entities:</strong> InventoryItem, Warehouse, PurchaseOrder, Supplier,
        ReorderRule
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Relationships:</strong> InventoryItem stored_in Warehouse, PurchaseOrder
        supplied_by Supplier
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Constraints:</strong> InventoryItem.quantity below threshold triggers
        ReorderRule
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Actions:</strong> CreatePurchaseOrder, UpdateInventoryCount, EscalateToManager
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This structured representation is what the agent actually reasons over.
      Get it right, and the agent almost builds itself.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        Treating fact tables as edges — an order is not a relationship between a
        customer and a product. It is an independent entity connected to both
        via separate edges.
      </li>
      <li>
        Building visualization without actions — a knowledge graph without
        action buttons is just a pretty picture.
      </li>
      <li>
        Skipping constraints — entities without rules lead to agents that
        produce impossible states.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "projects/prompt-to-ontology")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Prompt-to-Ontology Project
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/agent-product-design")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Agent Product Design
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
